lessons.motivation:
Before C++26, a `constexpr` function could not use `throw`: if a `throw` expression was reachable during constant evaluation, the program was ill-formed — the compiler refused to evaluate such a constant. This created an awkward dilemma when writing generic `constexpr` functions with input validation.

The old alternatives looked like this:

```cpp
// Option 1: static_assert — but doesn't work when the constraint
// can't be expressed as a boolean template parameter
constexpr int old_divide(int a, int b) {
    // can't throw — return a "magic" sentinel value
    return b == 0 ? INT_MIN : a / b;
}

// Option 2: std::optional — cumbersome for chains of calls
constexpr std::optional<int> safe_div(int a, int b) {
    if (b == 0) return std::nullopt;
    return a / b;
}
```

Both approaches mixed logic and error handling, made signatures more complex, and couldn't be used when the same `constexpr` function needed to be called both at compile time and at runtime with different error conventions.

**P3068** (C++26) removes this restriction: `throw` and `try`/`catch` are now allowed in `constexpr` functions. A thrown exception must be caught within the same constant expression — otherwise the evaluation terminates with a compile error. The runtime behavior of the function remains completely normal: exceptions work as usual there.

lessons.theory:
## What P3068 Allows

In C++26, `throw` expressions and `try`/`catch` blocks are fully allowed inside `constexpr` functions. The key rule: **an exception thrown during constant evaluation must be caught within the same constant expression**. If it escapes, the evaluation ends with a compile error (ill-formed), not UB.

```cpp
constexpr int validate(int n) {
    if (n < 0) throw std::invalid_argument("negative");
    return n;
}

// OK: exception caught within the constant expression
constexpr int x = []() -> int {
    try { return validate(-1); }
    catch (...) { return 0; }
}();

// Ill-formed: throw not caught — compile error
// constexpr int y = validate(-1);  // error!
```

`catch (...)` also works in `constexpr` context and catches any exception type.

## Exception Types

The type of the thrown object must be **constexpr-constructible** — that is, the exception object's constructor must itself be executable in a constant context. Standard library classes `std::exception`, `std::invalid_argument`, `std::out_of_range`, `std::domain_error` and others are supported by implementations, though the standard does not formally require their `constexpr` constructors — GCC implements this in practice. A user-defined type works if it is a *literal type* with a `constexpr` constructor.

## Uncaught Throw = Ill-Formed (Compile Error)

If during constant expression evaluation an exception remains uncaught until the end of that evaluation, the compiler issues an error — this is **not** UB, it is a diagnosable error:

```
error: uncaught exception of type 'std::invalid_argument'; 'what()': 'negative'
```

Importantly: at runtime the same function works completely normally — the exception just propagates up the call stack as usual. The compile error only occurs when trying to evaluate a `constexpr` result.

## Interaction with noexcept

`noexcept` on a `constexpr` function does not affect the ability to throw during compilation — `noexcept` describes **runtime** behavior. A function without `noexcept` can throw both at compile time and at runtime. A function with `noexcept` will call `std::terminate` on a runtime throw, as usual — P3068 does not change this.

`noexcept(expr)` when evaluating the specifier does *not* evaluate the expression — this is an unevaluated context, so a constexpr exception does not arise there.

## Interaction with if consteval

You can throw exceptions only in the compile-time branch of `if consteval`, leaving the runtime branch clean or using a different error strategy:

```cpp
constexpr int safe_op(int n) {
    if consteval {
        if (n < 0) throw std::domain_error("negative at compile time");
    }
    // runtime branch: different error approach
    return n < 0 ? 0 : n;
}
```

## Unevaluated Contexts

The body of a `constexpr` function containing `throw` is **not** ill-formed on its own: the compiler analyzes throw only during actual constant expression evaluation. In unevaluated contexts (`sizeof`, `decltype`, `noexcept(f())`) the function is not called, so the throw path is never reached — no error.

## SFINAE and Templates

An uncaught throw in a constexpr evaluation is a **hard error** (compile error), not a substitution failure. It is **not** grounds for SFINAE/excluding a template candidate from consideration. If you need to conditionally check whether an evaluation will throw, use a `requires` expression with an explicit check or a separate constexpr-evaluable boolean flag.

If a template parameter affects whether the `throw` path is reached, the constant expression will be ill-formed for specific arguments, but not as a substitution failure — the compiler will issue an error.

## Old Alternatives vs P3068

| Approach | Before C++26 | With P3068 |
|----------|--------------|------------|
| Return `std::optional` | Primary method | Still used; now a style choice |
| "Magic" values / sentinels | Common | Avoid: loses information |
| `static_assert` | Only for template conditions | Complemented by try/catch |
| `throw` + `try`/`catch` | Ill-formed in constexpr | **Fully works** |

## Ill-Formed vs UB: Summary

Uncaught throw during constant evaluation → **compile error** (ill-formed), not UB. The same function works normally at runtime. This is fundamental: there is no "silent" violation, the compiler always diagnoses the problem.

examples.code:
#include <print>
#include <stdexcept>

constexpr int safe_divide(int a, int b) {
    if (b == 0)
        throw std::invalid_argument("division by zero");
    return a / b;
}

int main() {
    // Caught at compile time -- no runtime exception
    constexpr int result = []() -> int {
        try {
            return safe_divide(10, 2);
        } catch (const std::invalid_argument&) {
            return -1;
        }
    }();
    std::print("result = {}\n", result);

    // Runtime call works as usual
    int x = safe_divide(21, 7);
    std::print("runtime: {}\n", x);
}

#include <print>
#include <stdexcept>

constexpr int parse_positive(int n) {
    if (n <= 0)
        throw std::domain_error("must be positive");
    return n * n;
}

// Wrapper: catches the compile-time exception, returns sentinel
constexpr int checked_square(int n) {
    try {
        return parse_positive(n);
    } catch (const std::domain_error&) {
        return -1;  // sentinel -- signals an error
    }
}

int main() {
    constexpr int a = checked_square(5);    // normal path
    constexpr int b = checked_square(-3);   // exception caught -> sentinel
    std::print("a={} b={}\n", a, b);
}

#include <print>
#include <stdexcept>

constexpr int bounded(int v, int lo, int hi) {
    if (v < lo || v > hi)
        throw std::out_of_range("value out of bounds");
    return v;
}

// noexcept(false): function may throw at runtime
static_assert(!noexcept(bounded(0, 0, 1)));

int main() {
    // Runtime: exception propagates normally
    try {
        int x = bounded(99, 0, 10);
        std::print("x={}\n", x);
    } catch (const std::out_of_range& e) {
        std::print("caught: {}\n", e.what());
    }

    // Compile-time: exception caught inside the constant expression
    constexpr int y = []() -> int {
        try {
            return bounded(5, 0, 10);
        } catch (...) {
            return -1;
        }
    }();
    std::print("compile-time y={}\n", y);
}

#include <print>

// Literal type -- constexpr-constructible
struct CompileError {
    const char* msg;
    constexpr const char* what() const { return msg; }
};

constexpr int parse_index(int idx, int size) {
    if (idx < 0 || idx >= size)
        throw CompileError{"index out of range"};
    return idx;
}

constexpr int safe_get(int idx) {
    constexpr int arr[] = {10, 20, 30, 40, 50};
    try {
        int i = parse_index(idx, 5);
        return arr[i];
    } catch (const CompileError& e) {
        return -1;  // could also use e.what() at compile time
    }
}

int main() {
    constexpr int a = safe_get(2);    // valid index
    constexpr int b = safe_get(10);   // out of range -> sentinel
    std::print("a={} b={}\n", a, b);
}

