lessons.theory:
## Signature and header

```cpp
#include <type_traits>   // or <memory> — P2637 specifies <type_traits>

template<typename T>
consteval bool std::is_within_lifetime(const T* p) noexcept;
```

`std::is_within_lifetime` is a `consteval` function: it can only be called in a **constant-evaluated context** (inside `consteval` functions, `constexpr` evaluations, `static_assert`, etc.). Attempting to call it in an ordinary runtime function is a **compile error**.

## What it returns

- **`true`** — `p` points to an object whose lifetime is currently active in the constant evaluation: an ordinary live variable, an active `union` member, an array element, etc.
- **`false`** — `p` is a null pointer, a pointer to an inactive `union` member, or an object whose lifetime has not yet started or has already ended.

> **Implementation note (2026):** `std::is_within_lifetime` as a `std::` function is not yet implemented in either GCC trunk or Clang trunk. Clang trunk exposes the compiler primitive `__builtin_is_within_lifetime` with the same semantics, which will underpin the standard function. The examples in this lesson use `__builtin_is_within_lifetime` directly; in final C++26 the code will need to switch to `std::is_within_lifetime` from `<type_traits>`.

## The main scenario: `union` and the active member

At any point in time a `union` has exactly one active member. Accessing an inactive member in a `constexpr` context is **ill-formed**. To safely pick a branch, you must first know which member is active. That is precisely what `is_within_lifetime` is for:

```cpp
consteval bool example() {
    union { int i; double d; } u;
    u.i = 42;
    bool i_active = std::is_within_lifetime(&u.i);  // true
    bool d_active = std::is_within_lifetime(&u.d);  // false
    return i_active && !d_active;
}
static_assert(example());
```

Assigning `u.i` makes `int` the active member; `double` stops being active. `is_within_lifetime` reflects this instantly.

## Connection to `constexpr optional` and union-based types

The standard `std::optional<T>` internally uses `union { T value; char dummy; }` plus a separate `bool` to track whether the value is present. With `is_within_lifetime` that `bool` is no longer needed — the compiler itself tracks `union` member activation:

```cpp
template<typename T>
struct ConstexprMaybe {
    union { T value; char empty; };
    constexpr ConstexprMaybe()      : empty(0) {}
    constexpr ConstexprMaybe(T val) { std::construct_at(&value, val); }

    consteval bool has_value() const {
        return std::is_within_lifetime(&value);
    }
};
```

## Rules and limitations

**Consteval context only.** Because `is_within_lifetime` is itself `consteval`, calling it from an ordinary function (`bool f(const int* p) { return std::is_within_lifetime(p); }`) is a compile error. This is intentional: the notion of "object within its lifetime" simply makes no sense as a runtime query through a pointer whose value is unknown at compile time.

**No SFINAE.** `is_within_lifetime` is `consteval`, so its call failures are hard errors, not substitution failures. You cannot use it for SFINAE.

**Null pointer — error or `false`?** Per the P2637 specification, a null pointer yields `false`. However, current implementations (`__builtin_is_within_lifetime` in Clang) produce a hard compile-time error when `nullptr` is passed. Do not pass `nullptr` directly — check the pointer first.

**One-past-the-end pointer.** Similarly: specification says `false`, current Clang builtin gives a compile error. Check your indices before calling.

**Sub-objects (struct members, array elements).** If the owning object is alive, its members are also considered "within lifetime":

```cpp
consteval bool test() {
