## Old alternatives and why is_within_lifetime is better

| Approach | Problem |
|---|---|
| Manual `bool` discriminant | Must synchronise manually; wastes a byte; forgetting to update → silent bug |
| Access without check | Ill-formed in constexpr; UB at runtime (type punning) |
| `std::variant` | Overhead; overkill for constexpr optional |
| `is_within_lifetime` | Zero overhead; semantics enforced by the compiler, not the programmer |

## Nuance checklist

- **Unevaluated contexts** (`sizeof`, `decltype`, `noexcept`): the function is not actually called in an unevaluated context, so no ill-formed — but the call also has no useful meaning.
- **Constexpr vs consteval**: a function whose body contains a call to `is_within_lifetime` automatically becomes `consteval` (if it was not already `constexpr`). This changes the class interface: a `has_value()` method with `is_within_lifetime` cannot be called in a runtime context.
- **Old code with a bool flag**: it remains correct and useful for runtime contexts. `is_within_lifetime` expands the capabilities of `constexpr` code without replacing runtime patterns.
- **GCC trunk (gsnapshot)**: as of the time this lesson was written, GCC trunk has neither `std::is_within_lifetime` nor an equivalent builtin — use Clang trunk (`clang_trunk` on Compiler Explorer).

